body:
Please remove `final` from `wincolor_sink::log()` (and possibly other member functions such as `flush()`).

Rationale: consider the code like this

```cpp
class ConsoleSink : public spdlog::sinks::stderr_color_sink_mt
{
public:
  ConsoleSink()
  {
    // Show just the message text in the console output, we don't want any extra
    // details like time, message level etc in it.
    set_pattern("%v");
  }

  void log(const spdlog::details::log_msg &msg) override
  {
    // Do something before logging [...]

    // Call the base class implementation to do the actual logging.
    spdlog::sinks::stderr_color_sink_mt::log(msg);

    // Possibly do something else after logging [...]
  }
};
```

It compiles and works fine under Unix when `stdout_color_sink_mt` is a `ansicolor_sink_mt`, but fails to compile under Windows when it is `wincolor_stderr_sink_mt`. IMO there is no reason for `log()` to be final in the latter class, especially if it's not final in the former.

As it stands, this has to be worked around by defining a delegating logger, but this is just unnecessary extra work which could be avoided and comes as a nasty surprise when porting from Unix to Windows.

I can make the trivial PR doing this if the maintainers agree to do it, of course, please let me know if I should.
